[ChapterName "2.Nf3 and the New Move - 5.Nbd2!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/kKcyAydw/ylW0na91"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 { This is perhaps the "classic" or slightly less modern version
of the London, as people have since discovered that there are at least some
nuances and small benefits to delaying Nf3 if you're strictly set on the
London. But really it comes down to taste and which main positions you're
interested in reaching. Le Quang Liem prefers this move, and other authors
like Sedlak and Romero Holmes prefer 2.Bf4 instead. } 2... Nf6 3. Bf4 c5 4. e3 Nc6 5. Nbd2! Nh5!? { A very combative
move that gambits the c-pawn. Black will grab the two bishops and wreck
White's pawn structure a bit in return, and will seek to open up lines down
the road with either ...d4 or ...b6 to whip up play in the center or queenside.
This move has been played recently by theoretical pioneers like Alexander
Grischuk, Fabiano Caruana, and Ivan Cheparinov, as well as our 2021 World
Rapid Champ Nodirbek Abdusattorov, who's scored 4/5 from here in 2021 alone. } { [%cal Gf4g5,Gf4e5,Gf4g3] } (5... Qb6 { is still possible here, but allows White to demonstrate the point of
his move order by taking on c5. } 6. dxc5 Qxb2 7. Rb1 Qc3 8. Bb5 { [%csl Rc3][%cal Rf3e5,Yb5e8,Bc2c4] } (8. Bd3 g6 9. O-O Bg7 { is generally fine for Black - White even needs to be careful to not
lose the c5-pawn for nothing. }) 8... g6 9. e4!? (9. O-O { generally allows
Black to finish their development and be fine, e.g. } 9... Bg7 10. Nb3 (10. Ne5 Qxc5 11. c4 O-O 12. Nb3 Qa3 13. Nxc6 bxc6 14. Bxc6 Bf5 15. Bxa8 Bxb1 16. Qxb1 Rxa8 17. Rc1 { G.Kamsky - B.Bok, internet blitz 2021 and now perhaps the active } 17... Ne4! { is the strongest. }) 10... O-O 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Be5 Qc4 (12... Bd7 { was Ding's choice against Carlsen and is also fine }) 13. Nfd4 Qa4! { and Black was fine in A.Kaliksteyn - T.Ringoir, Charlotte 2021 }) 9... dxe4 { I'm honestly still not certain what's happening after the mind-bending
complications starting with the piece sac } (9... a6! { is safer and
ultimately probably better, but even here it's hard for me to really
understand and break down what's happening - play is very move-by-move,
hand-to-hand combat style. }) 10. Be5 Qa5 11. O-O! { for instance } 11... exf3 12. Bxc6+ bxc6 13. Qxf3 { [%cal Gf3c6,Ge5f6,Gf1e1] } 13... Nd5! (13... Bd7? 14. Bxf6 exf6 15. Nc4 $18 { and Black
is never making it out of this alive. }) 14. Bxh8 Qxd2 15. c4 (15. Ba1?? Qxc2 { and Black's two pieces and a pawn for the rook plus that ultra stable rock on
d5 would leave them winning. }) 15... f6! { Ensuring the bishop doesn't come
out for a long time. } 16. Rfd1 Qf4 17. cxd5 Qxf3 18. gxf3 Bf5 19. Rb7 O-O-O 20. Rxa7 Kb8 21. Ra6 cxd5 22. Rd4 $13 { and the game is still a total mess. }) 6. dxc5 (6. Bg5 h6! { As usual after ...Nh5, we continue the harassment of this
bishop } 7. Bh4 g5 8. Ne5! (8. Bg3? Nxg3 9. hxg3 g4! 10. Ne5 Nxe5 11. dxe5 Bg7 $17 { G.Kamsky - P.Shuvalova, Internet rapid 2022 }) 8... Nxe5 9. dxe5 (9. Qxh5 Nc6 { wins the d4-pawn, and if White gets
greedy with } 10. Bxg5 { then } 10... Rg8! 11. Bf4 e5! 12. Bg3 Bg4 13. Qh4 Qb6 $40 { gives Black a crushing initiative. }) 9... Ng7 10. Bg3 Nf5 11. Qf3!? Bg7 12. Bb5+ Bd7 13. Qxf5 Bxb5 14. e6 fxe6 15. Qg6+ Kf8 16. Qxe6 Qd7 17. Qxd7 Bxd7 $15 { B.Korpa - J.Pechac Czech Republic 2021 }) (6. Be5 e6 (6... f6 { right away is
less precise because of } 7. c4! fxe5? 8. cxd5 Qxd5 9. Bc4 Qd6 10. Ng5! $40) 7. c3 f6 8. Bg3 cxd4 9. exd4 g6! (9... Nxg3 { opens the h-file too soon
and causes Black some problem, e.g. } 10. hxg3 g6 11. Bd3 { and Black must play
the ugly ...Kf7, since } 11... Bg7? { loses to } 12. Rxh7!) 10. Bd3 Bg7 11. O-O O-O { and Black had a good position in A.Korobov - B.Gelfand, Spanish Team
Championships 2021 }) (6. Bg3 cxd4 7. exd4 g6 8. Be2 Bg7 9. c3 Nxg3 10. hxg3 O-O 11. O-O Qc7 $10 { T.Franzen - J.Mulder, Correspondence 2019 }) 6... Nxf4 7. exf4 { [%csl Yc5,Yc2,Yf2,Yf4,Gf8,Gc8] } 7... g6! { The Black bishop heads to g7 (perhaps with an h6
pitstop on the way), hoping for eventual long diagonal domination after Black
gets ...d4 in. } 8. c3 { White has generally played this move first to preserve
maximum minor piece flexibility, reasoning that it's going to be necessary
regardless. } (8. Bb5 Qc7! { [%csl Gf4] } (8... Qa5 9. Nd4 { is sort of annoying in this case,
displaying one difference between 8.Bd3 and the text }) 9. g3 Bg7 { [%cal Gg7b2] } 10. c3 O-O 11. O-O (11. Nb3 { first allows an interesting idea in } 11... Na5!? { and if White hops
in with } 12. Qxd5 { then } 12... Be6 13. Qd1 Nxb3 14. axb3 Rfd8 15. Qe2 Qxc5 $132 { sees Black regain the pawn soon with a fantastic position. }) 11... d4! 12. Bxc6 (12. cxd4 Nxd4 13. Nxd4 Bxd4 $15 { [%csl Gb2,Gc5] }) 12... dxc3 13. Be4 (13. bxc3? Qxc6 $19 { and White is probably close to positionally lost already - huge structural
problems and Black's raking bishop pair will give White terrible problems. }) 13... cxd2 14. Qxd2 Qxc5 $15 { [%csl Gc8,Gg7] }) (8. Bd3?! { is a little too mundane and doesn't
really meet the demands of the position, e.g. } 8... Qa5! { White can't stop ...
Qxc5, and so I doubt Black has any problems here. You could make a decent case
that Black is probably already better on account of their structure and two
bishops. } { [%cal Gd2b3] } (8... Bg7 $146 9. c3 d4! 10. cxd4 Nxd4 $132 { also gives Black
great compensation. }) 9. O-O Qxc5 { [%csl Gf8,Gc8,Yf2,Yf4] } 10. Nb3 Qd6 11. Qd2 Bg7 12. c3 O-O 13. Rfe1 Bg4 (13... Bh6!? 14. g3 e5! $36) 14. Qe3 Bxf3 15. Qxf3 e6 16. h4 h5 $15 { M.Carlsen - F.Caruana, online rapid 2020 }) 8... Bh6! { Black first induces
weaknesses in the kingside light squares before returning the bishop to g7
where it ultimately belongs. } 9. g3 { [%csl Rh3,Rg2,Rg4,Rf3] } 9... O-O 10. Nb3 (10. Bg2 b6 11. cxb6 Qxb6 12. Nb3 (12. O-O Rd8) 12... Ba6! 13. Qxd5 e5! $36) 10... Bg7 { With it's job done on h6,
Black's bishop heads to greener pastures. } (10... a5 { was tried by Grischuk
against Sarin here, but I tend to think it's less accurate here because of } 11. a4! { because the followup } 11... b6 { can be met by the very annoying } 12. Bb5! $16) 11. Bg2 (11. h4 { L.Aronian-N.Abdusattorov, FIDE Grand Swiss 2021 } 11... a5!? $146 12. h5 (12. Be2 b6 13. cxb6 Qxb6 $132) 12... a4 13. Nbd4 Bg4 14. hxg6 Nxd4! 15. gxh7+ Kh8 16. cxd4 Qa5+ 17. Ke2 { [%csl Re2] } 17... Ra6 $40 { [%cal Ga6e6] }) (11. Bb5 Bh3 12. Bf1 Bg4 (12... Bc8) 13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 e6 15. Bb5 a5! 16. a4 Na7 17. O-O b6! $132) 11... a5! { with the White bishop no longer able to slide over b5, this is
well time now. Black weakens the White queenside, especially the b3-square,
before breaking with ...b6. An important theme to understand. } 12. a4 (12. Nbd4 Bg4 13. O-O Nxd4 14. cxd4 b6 $132) 12... b6! 13. cxb6 Rb8! { Black finds a
way to double on b-file without immediately allowing White to smack on d5. } (13... Qxb6? 14. Qxd5! Be6 15. Qb5 $16 { defends to White's advantage. }) 14. O-O Qxb6 15. Nfd4 Nxd4 16. Nxd4 e6 17. Nb5 Ba6 $15 { Black regains the pawn and
will still have pressure. } *


[Event "An Attacking Repertoire AGAINST the London: 2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c3!? - Le Quang Liem's Choice"]
[Date "2022.01.07"]
[White "London"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "TonyRo"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D02"]
[Opening "Queen's Pawn Game: Symmetrical Variation"]
[StudyName "An Attacking Repertoire AGAINST the London"]
[ChapterName "2.Nf3 Nf6 3.c3!? - Le Quang Liem's Choice"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/kKcyAydw/g3w1sArq"]

1. d4 d5 2. Nf3 { This is perhaps the "classic" or slightly less modern version
of the London, as people have since discovered that there are at least some
nuances and small benefits to delaying Nf3 if you're strictly set on the
London. But really it comes down to taste and which main positions you're
interested in reaching. Le Quang Liem prefers this move, and other authors
like Sedlak and Romero Holmes prefer 2.Bf4 instead. } 2... Nf6 3. c3!? { is a VERY new and "meta" move order
that seeks to discourage the ...c5-break, which has obviously proven to
historically be a principled and sound answer to the London. We're going to
play it anyway! } 3... c5! 4. dxc5 { This is the idea, basically reaching a Reversed
Slav. } { [%csl Gc3] } (4. Bf4 Nc6 5. e3 Qb6 6. Qb3 { transposes to the old main line }) 4... e6 5. b4 (5. Be3!? { is a computer recommendation and was played by Rapport
against Shankland recently, so it deserves to be checked as well. } 5... Be7 6. g3 O-O 7. Bg2 a5 8. O-O { was the logical course of R.Rapport - S.Shankland, St.
Louis rapid 2019. Perhaps better than Shanklands ...Na6 was } 8... Nc6! $146 { , the point being that now the critical idea } 9. c4 { can be met by } 9... Ng4 10. Bf4 d4! { with a solid position for Black after ...Bxc5. }) 5... a5 6. e3 (6. Qb3 b6! { [%cal Gc5b6] } 7. cxb6 Qxb6 (7... axb4 8. cxb4 Qxb6 9. b5) 8. Be3 Qb7 9. bxa5 Rxa5 10. Qxb7 Bxb7 11. Nbd2 Nbd7 12. Nb3 Ra4 13. g3 Be7 (13... Bd6 $146) 14. Bg2 (14. Bd4!?) 14... O-O 15. O-O Rfa8 16. Nc1 Ne4 17. Rb1 Ba6 18. Rb3 Bf6) 6... axb4 7. cxb4 b6 8. Bb5+ { Lopping the LSBs off seems to be the main choice here. } (8. a4 { White can also leave the light-squared bishops on the board, e.g. } 8... bxc5 9. b5 (9. Bb5+ { transposes to 8.Bb5+ }) 9... Bd6 10. Bb2 Nbd7 11. Nbd2 O-O 12. Be2 (12. Bd3? e5!) 12... Bb7 13. O-O Bc7 14. Qc2 c4!? { , with a
typical Noteboom-esque mess. I am guessing that White typically exchanges them
based upon the rational that the White light-squared bishop is worse on e2 (it
wishes it was on d3) than Black's on b7, but also that the thematic e4-break
is tougher to acheive with Be2 and ...Bb7 inserted too. }) 8... Bd7 9. Bxd7+ Nbxd7 10. a4 bxc5 11. b5 { We've transposed to some sort of bizarre reversed
pseudo-Noteboom. In a true Noteboom reversed White would have exchanged bishop
for knight, but instead we traded light-squared bishops. I am not sure if this
really favors one side or the other, but it does change the flavor of the
position a bit - Black does not have the two bishops advantage, but } { [%csl Bb5,Ba4,Gd5,Gc5] } 11... Bd6 { I think this is the easiest and safest idea -
Black will just follow up with ...Bc7, ...O-O, and go from there. } (11... g5!? 12. Bb2 Bd6 13. Qe2 g4 14. Nfd2 { [%cal Gd8c7,Gd8b8] } 14... Qb8 { Relative to ..
.Qc7, this has the advantage of allowing ...Bc7-a5, but does stand in the way
of Black connecting rooks. } (14... Qc7 15. e4 Be5 (15... O-O 16. a5! { works tactically, and seems risky for Black to allow }) 16. Bxe5 Qxe5 17. Ra3 O-O 18. Nc3 c4 $13 { was a total mess in M.Zarnescu - T.Pekin, Correspondence
2020 }) 15. f4 { The easiest way for White to castle. } 15... gxf3 16. Nxf3 Rg8 17. O-O Bc7 $13 { (line by Le Quang Liem) }) (11... Ra7!? 12. O-O Qa8 13. Bd2 Bd6 14. a5! $146 (14. Nc3 Bc7! { was
probably more comfortable for Black in M.Bluebaum-W.So, internet rapid 2021
given his dark-squared blockade on the queenside. } { [%cal Gd6c7,Gc7b6,Gb6a5] }) 14... O-O 15. Na3 Ne4 (15... Rb8?! 16. b6! Nxb6 17. Nb5! Nc4 18. Nxa7 Qxa7 19. Bc3 $14 { is the
Lifetime Repertoire author's devious idea! }) 16. a6 $13 { is Le Quang Liem's
improvement over the So game. I am not a huge fan of allowing this pawn to a6
(why go ...Ra7 and ...Qa7 if this is still possible for White?), but I'll let
the reader decide. }) 12. Bb2 O-O 13. O-O Bc7 { [%csl Rb5,Ra4][%cal Gc7a5] } 14. Nbd2 Qe7 15. Qc2! { White keeps an eye on a4 and loads up the
e4-break as well. } (15. Bc3? e5! { [%cal Ge3e4,Gd5d4] } 16. a5 (16. e4 d4 17. Bb2 Ne8! $17) 16... e4 17. Ne1 d4 18. exd4 cxd4 19. Bb2 (19. Bxd4 Qd6 $19) 19... Qe5) 15... Ra7 16. h3 Rfa8 17. e4 $13 *


[Event "An Attacking Repertoire AGAINST the London: 2.Bf4 c5!"]
[Date "2022.01.07"]
[White "London"]
[Result "*"]
[Annotator "TonyRo"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "D00"]
[Opening "Queen's Pawn Game: Accelerated London System, Steinitz Countergambit"]
[StudyName "An Attacking Repertoire AGAINST the London"]
[ChapterName "2.Bf4 c5!"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/kKcyAydw/8AxFAr4d"]

1. d4 d5 2. Bf4 { Chucking the
bishop out there on move 2 is a slightly more modern move order it seems. Not
only does White retain more options in 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bf4, e.g. the Jobava lines,
Pircs, etc, there are also nuances to 1...d5 2.Bf4 as well. Delaying Nf3 in
favor of e3/c3 allows Qb3 one move earlier, and not inserting Nf3/...Nf6 also
leaves the d-pawn undefended in some important lines, e.g. the note to 6...Bf5
in our main line below. } 2... c5 3. e3 (3. e4!? { Entering an Albin Countergambit
Reversed where White has the free move Bf4. Weird! } { [%csl Gf4] } 3... Nc6!? { This is the most
pragmatic choice, which is a good way to go when facing a strange gambit line
you're likely to see in 1/1000 games or more! } (3... dxe4 4. d5 Nf6 5. Nc3 g6 { also seems totally playable, but is messier and requires Black find some
tricky moves. Not ideal for such a rare line. }) 4. exd5 (4. Nc3 cxd4 5. exd5 dxc3 6. dxc6 Qxd1+ 7. Rxd1 bxc6 8. Bc7 Bg4 9. f3 Bd7 $10 { F.Hoffmeyer - S.
Eichner, Bundesliga 2013 }) 4... Qxd5 5. Nc3 (5. dxc5 Qxd1+ 6. Kxd1 e5 7. Be3 Nf6 $10 { [%cal Gf6d5,Gf6g4] }) 5... Qxd4 6. Nd5 e5 7. Nc7+ Kd8 8. Nxa8 exf4 9. Nf3 Qxd1+ 10. Rxd1+ Bd7 11. Bb5 Kc8 12. O-O { A.Ostrovskiy - C.Holt,
